Mutational signatures analysis: de novo mutational signature extraction

During this practical session, we will focus on the detection and interpretation of mutational signatures in real samples. Particularly, youll perform the de novo signature extraction and signature identification.

The data used in this section is publicly available WES data generated from Ji et at. 2020 and somatic mutation calls provided in the MutationalPatterns package. The somatic variant calling for the Ji et al 2020 data was performed using Strelka2.

To run all these analysis, we will work with the R package MutationalPatterns.

Preparing and loading the data

Functions to load vcf.gz Strelka2 files

This function can open the Strelka2 somatic calls ( vcf.gz with SNVs) and extract the VAF, DP, number of alternative alleles

# Function to load snp.vcf.gz from Strelka2
Load_vcf <- function(vcf_file){
  VCF <- as.data.frame(fread(cmd = paste("zgrep -v '##' ", vcf_file, sep = ''), sep = '\t'))
  VCF <- dplyr::rename(VCF, CHROM = `#CHROM`)
  VCF <- VCF[VCF$CHROM %in% c(paste('chr',seq(1,22), sep = ''),'chrX','chrY'),]
  
  # Parse the vcf to extract alternative counts
  # We keep only the PASS mutations
  VCF2 <- VCF[VCF$FILTER == 'PASS',]
  
  # Extract normal alternative counts
  VCF2 <- tidyr::separate(data = VCF2, col = NORMAL, sep = ':', 
                          into = c('N_DP','N_FDP','N_SDP','N_SUBDP','N_AU','N_CU','N_GU','N_TU'))
  VCF2$N_REF_COUNT <- apply(VCF2, 1, function(x) as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(x = x[paste('N_',x['REF'],'U', sep = '')], split = ','))[1]))
  VCF2$N_ALT_COUNT <- apply(VCF2, 1, function(x) as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(x = x[paste('N_',x['ALT'],'U', sep = '')], split = ','))[1]))
  VCF2$N_DP <- as.numeric(VCF2$N_DP) # We want this value to be considered as a number
  
  # Extract tumour alternative counts
  VCF2 <- tidyr::separate(data = VCF2, col = TUMOR, sep = ':', 
                          into = c('T_DP','T_FDP','T_SDP','T_SUBDP','T_AU','T_CU','T_GU','T_TU'))
  VCF2$T_REF_COUNT <- apply(VCF2, 1, function(x) as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(x = x[paste('T_',x['REF'],'U', sep = '')], split = ','))[1]))
  VCF2$T_ALT_COUNT <- apply(VCF2, 1, function(x) as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(x = x[paste('T_',x['ALT'],'U', sep = '')], split = ','))[1]))
  VCF2$T_DP <- as.numeric(VCF2$T_DP) # We want this value to be considered as a number
  
  # Too many columns for now, let's keep only the important ones
  VCF3 <- VCF2[,c('CHROM','POS','REF','ALT','QUAL','FILTER','N_DP','N_REF_COUNT','N_ALT_COUNT','T_DP','T_REF_COUNT','T_ALT_COUNT')]
  
  # Compute Variant Allele Frequency (VAF) in the matched normal sample
  VCF3$N_VAF <- VCF3$N_ALT_COUNT/VCF3$N_DP
  # Compute Variant Allele Frequency (VAF) in the tumour sample
  VCF3$T_VAF <- VCF3$T_ALT_COUNT/VCF3$T_DP
  return(VCF3)
}

# Directory with the Strelka2 calls

length(files)
## [1] 9


In order to save the calls of all these files in a single data frame automatically, we will use the next for loop:

count <- 1
Mut_calls <- NULL
for (file in files){
  # Load vcf.gz file
  # Function previously defined
  a <- Load_vcf(file)
  
  # Get sample ID
  # We extract the sample name from the full path
  sampleID <- rev(unlist(strsplit(x = file, split = '/')))[3]
  
  if (nrow(a) > 0){
    a <- cbind(sampleID,a)

    Mut_calls[[count]] <- a
    
    count <- count + 1
  }
}

# Usually faster than rbind in each iteration of the for loop
Mut_calls <- do.call("rbind", Mut_calls)

Mutation characteristics

In this example today, we will focus on SNVs. This package ( MutationalPatterns), works with GRanges objects. For these reasons, we will transform our data frame with mutations into a GRanges object:
It can be done with this function:

# Transform data.frame to genomic ranges object
# Create list of granges
GRmaker <- function(CALLS,GROUP){
  TEMP <- CALLS[CALLS$GROUP == GROUP,]
  GR <- with(TEMP, GRanges(CHROM, ranges=IRanges(POS, POS), REF = REF,ALT = ALT))
  seqlevelsStyle(GR) <- "UCSC"
  GenomeInfoDb::genome(GR) <- 'hg38'
  return (GR)
}


Once defined this function, we can execute it using our mutations data frame:

# This column will specify how to group the mutations
# For now, we use the sampleID, but it can be modified
Mut_calls$GROUP <- Mut_calls$sampleID

# Create list of granges
GROUPS <- unique(Mut_calls$GROUP)
G_lists <-  lapply(GROUPS, function(x) GRmaker(Mut_calls, x))
names(G_lists) <- GROUPS

96 mutation profile

The 96 mutation profile refers to a classification system that characterizes mutations based on the nucleotide context surrounding them. It considers all possible trinucleotide combinations (96 in total) and quantifies the frequency of specific mutation types within each context.

First we need to generate a 96 trinucleotide mutation count matrix using the function mut_matrix:

mut_mat <- mut_matrix(vcf_list = G_lists, ref_genome = ref_genome)

De novo mutational signature extraction using NMF

Mutational signatures are believed to depict underlying mutational processes and are characterized by their unique contribution of mutation types within specific sequence contexts. These signatures can be extracted from your mutation count matrix using a technique called non-negative matrix factorization (NMF).

Extracting the number of ranks (signatures)

In the context of NMF, an essential parameter is the factorization rank, which refers to the number of mutational signatures to be extracted. Determining the optimal factorization rank can be achieved by utilizing the NMF package. This package provides tools and methods to assist in identifying the most suitable factorization rank for the given analysis.


According to their paper: The most common approach is to choose the smallest rank for which cophenetic correlation coefficient starts decreasing. Another approach is to choose the rank for which the plot of the residual sum of squares (RSS) between the input matrix and its estimate shows an inflection point

# First add a small pseudocount to your mutation count matrix
mut_mat <- mut_mat + 0.0001
estimate <- nmf(mut_mat, rank = 2:5, method = "brunet", 
                nrun = 30, seed = 123456, .opt = "v-p")

Now, we can visualise the NMF results:

plot(estimate)

Based on the previous plot, we can now extract the the number of signatures to fit. In this case rank = 3 (because it is the point where the cophenetic correlation coefficient starts decreasing).

nmf_res <- extract_signatures(mut_mat, rank = 3, nrun = 10, single_core = TRUE)


We can name our extracted signatures:

colnames(nmf_res$signatures) <- c("Signature A", "Signature B","Signature C")
rownames(nmf_res$contribution) <- c("Signature A", "Signature B","Signature C")

And visualise them:

# You can plot the 96-profile of the signatures (When looking at SNVs)
plot_96_profile(nmf_res$signatures, condensed = TRUE)

Signature identification

Now, we want to identify if the extracted mutational signatures have potential underlying biological processes that we can characterise. This involves comparing the extracted signatures with known reference signatures and determining the most similar matches based on various metrics (e.g., cosine similarity).

Although we already named our new signatures, we can load the COSMIC signatures and try to find if any of our extracted signatures is very similar to the known ones.

For that, we will compare them (usine cosine similarities) against the already known signatures in COSMIC signatures (v3). We will change the name if they have a cosine similarity >= 0.85.

# Getting known signatures
# COSMIC (v3.2) (Alexandrov et al. 2020)
signatures = get_known_signatures()

# Rename mutational signatures
nmf_res <- rename_nmf_signatures(nmf_res, signatures, cutoff = 0.85)
colnames(nmf_res$signatures)
## [1] "SBS1-like"  "SBS5-like"  "SBS7b-like"

Visualizing the extracted signatures

We can now visualize the new signatures:

# You can plot the 96-profile of the signatures (When looking at SNVs)
plot_96_profile(nmf_res$signatures, condensed = TRUE)

Decomposing our initial samples with the new signatures

The process of signature refitting involves measuring the impact of a specific set of signatures on the mutational profile of a sample. This is particularly valuable when analyzing mutational signatures in small groups or individual samples, as well as for comparing ones own findings with established signatures and published research.

# You can visualize the contribution of the signatures in a barplot
plot_contribution(nmf_res$contribution, nmf_res$signature,
                  mode = "relative"
)

Evaluating the performance of the reconstruction using our new signatures

One of the most used methods for quantifying the performance of mutational signature analysis is using the cosine similarity. This is a measure used to quantify the similarity between two signature vectors. The cosine similarity calculates the cosine of the angle between two signature vectors, which indicates the degree of similarity or alignment between them.

# Check the reconstruction
Plot_reconstruciton_cos_sim <- plot_original_vs_reconstructed(mut_mat, nmf_res$reconstructed,y_intercept = 0.95)
Plot_reconstruciton_cos_sim

Are these signatures and patterns different across samples?

This function clusters the samples and signatures based on the different contribution. This is quite interesting if we want to compare samples between them, and check the different mutational processes working on each.

# Check how the samples cluster
plot_contribution_heatmap(nmf_res$contribution, 
                          cluster_samples = TRUE, 
                          cluster_sigs = TRUE)
